properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A significant rainfall is possible tonight into Sunday morning. A low pressure system will approach Southern Ontario today, with rain developing over the area this evening. Rain, heavy at times, will continue tonight into Sunday morning. Total rainfall amounts of 30 to 40 mm are possible, with the heaviest rain falling overnight tonight. Gusty southeasterly to southwesterly winds up to 60 km/h are possible, with the strongest winds occurring on Sunday. Rain will taper to scattered showers Sunday evening. Ensure that storm drains are clear of leaves and other debris. Heavy downpours can cause flash floods as well as water pooling on roads. Local power outages are possible. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.
Expires: 2019-10-27T09:51:26-00:00

properties.Title: Wind Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Strong winds that may cause damage are expected. High winds associated with a low pressure system moving in from the south are expected late Sunday morning. Southwesterly gusts of 80 km/h are likely and gusts of 90 km/h are possible. These severe winds should end by Sunday evening. ### Loose objects may be tossed by the wind and cause injury or damage. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Update: High Water Advisory Alert For Portions Of The Red River
properties.Summary:
Description: Update: This is a Manitoba Emergency Alert. Manitoba Infrastructure's Hydrologic Forecast Centre has issued a High Water Advisory for the Red River at Ste. Agathe, the Red River Floodway Inlet Control Structure, and within the City of Winnipeg due to expected high flows. If you are in the affected area, be watchful of local waterways as flooding is likely to occur. Do not attempt to cross fast flowing waters or waters of unknown depth. Avoid flooded areas. Follow all directions by the local authorities. Listen for updates and take all necessary precautions to stay safe. Up-to-date information is available at www.gov.mb.ca/flooding and www.manitoba511.ca or stay tuned to local media.
Expires: 2019-10-27T11:00:00-05:00

properties.Title: Snow Squall Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow squalls are expected to develop. Under the snow squall bands, visibilities will be significantly reduced due to the heavy snow, and snow will quickly accumulate. Conditions are favourable for the development of snow squalls over Great Slave Lake on Sunday. Heavy snow is expected to be localized to areas under the snow bands with total snowfall accumulations reaching near 25 cm. ### Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Snow squall watches are issued when conditions are favourable for the formation of bands of snow that could produce intense accumulating snow or near zero visibilities. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NTstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NTStorm.
Expires: 2019-10-27T19:16:27-00:00
